Successful Resection of a Retrohepatic Inferior Vena Cava Primary Leiomyosarcoma 
with Atrial Thrombus Extension in a 30-Week Pregnant Woman.

Nooromid MJ(1), Caicedo JC(2), Pham DT(3), Kundu SD(4), Eskandari MK(5).

Author information:
(1)Division of Vascular Surgery, Northwestern Feinberg School of Medicine, 
Chicago, IL.
(2)Division of Transplantation Surgery, Northwestern Feinberg School of 
Medicine, Chicago, IL.
(3)Division of Cardiac Surgery, Northwestern Feinberg School of Medicine, 
Chicago, IL.
(4)Department of Urology, Northwestern Feinberg School of Medicine, Chicago, IL.
(5)Division of Vascular Surgery, Northwestern Feinberg School of Medicine, 
Chicago, IL. Electronic address: meskanda@nm.org.

Leiomyosarcomas are an uncommon malignant subset of tumors accounting for 
approximately 20% of soft tissue sarcomas. Primary vascular leiomyosarcomas 
(PVLs) are a rare subset of leiomyosarcomas that may originate in the arterial 
or venous circulation but most commonly affect the inferior vena cava (IVC). 
PVLs more commonly affect women to men in a 2:1 ratio and most frequently occur 
in the fourth to sixth decades of life. Few reports have described this 
infrequent pathologic state in the setting of advanced pregnancy. Presented is a 
case of a 44-year-old 30-week pregnant woman who presented with a PVL of the 
retrohepatic IVC, which was complicated by occlusion of the IVC and tumor 
thrombus extension into the hepatic veins and right atrium. Herein, we describe 
our multidisciplinary management of this rare problem with successful surgical 
resection of her tumor and IVC reconstruction.

